The fact that the mage won't be casting as often or as repeatedly, due to the efficiency issues, will also be noticed.<br>
<br>
There's no good reason that this info wasn't always available. It's about time that they let everyone see it (if they want), IMO. <p><a href="http://www.EQPixelArmy.com" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/whiz/whiz-animated-banner-animation.gif" height="120" width="80" alt="EQPA" border=0></a><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=41790" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/whiz/whiz-animated-banner-text.gif" height=120 width=272 alt="Whizbang Dustyboots" border=0></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=teneran67>teneran67</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 49<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/3/03 11:03 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Mana efficiency is almost meaningless.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Define &quot;almost&quot;.<br>
<br>
Mana efficiency is real useful when I solo, I can kill much faster, and therefore get more exp per playtime, with better mana efficiency.<br>
<br>
Mana efficiency is also useful when raiding outside PoP.  Maybe you don't ever kill luclin bosses, or do zones like VT.  But there are plenty of fights in EQ which take a signiciant amount of time, or involve a lot of clearing.  And mana efficiency is surely nice to have then.<br>
<br>
In a perfect world, one would like to have the highest DPS, and mana efficiency.  And while efficiency may, in some contexts, not be important, its hardly almost meaningless.<br>
<br>
Teneran<br>
Arcanist - Dragon Army <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=grimstafftheurgist>Grimstaff Theurgist</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elder Arcanist</span><br>  Posts: 8165<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/3/03 11:08 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>So doing more nuke damage to a mob than a mage does is less important than how big the nuke you are using to do the damage is? Use Ice Comet. You can wow everyone with how big your nuke is while at the same time you cut your DPS to lower than the Mages. I have seen too many people concentrate on how big a nuke is when trying to compare Mages and Wizards, and even then they are usually trying to compare a bolt spell to a straight dd. All this stuff looks great on paper, but the actual reality is, you will be far ahead of the Mages. Big nukes are nice, but so are small nukes, if you know how to use them and don't get caught up worrying that someone else looks better than you even when they aren't. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I think the point is less penis envy and more concern at clueless or ignorant players looking at the big boom by the Mage and going &quot;when are you going to show you are a Wizard and outdamage this guy?&quot; while the pet is whaling away and casting.  They don't see casting time, they don't see mana cost, they see damage numbers scrolling by.  None of the stuff that makes Wizards technically superior matters to someone who is going by what they see in combat.<br>
<br>
That's one reason why I am opposed to spell damage numbers being shown, as I noted earlier.  Most people, even Wizards, are very unaware of the damage that other classes can actually do with their spells.  SOme of those spells cast faster than ours.<br>
<br>
For instance, were you aware that Mage AE Rain spells do more damage than Wizard ones post 50?  Its just one little bit of information that isn't widely known but will be if they make this change.  Resistances aren't shown.  If someone has spell effects off (many do at high level) they won't see anything from you if there's a full resist - just you slacking off because nothing happened.  Your stun does decent damage but not huge numbers, but its very useful because its a stun.  Do they notice the stun?  Maybe, but they'll probably notice that lower damage number scroll by.<br>
<br>
See how this works?  It isn't as simple as &quot;d00d people will see my l337 numberZ!!&quot; <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=moozoo>moozoo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 30<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/3/03 11:32 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re</span><hr size=1> I think spell damage reporting should always be enabled on the test server. It makes a lot of sense to test class balance etc on the test server.<br>
<br>
I do think that having spell damage displayed on the normal servers will make the game more competitive. Wizards with 200+ aa SoS and good gear (ID4 etc) will be more visably better than a wizard with 22 aa no SoS (or GSS or Enricks or agnarrs /sigh) such as myself. The way the game works is power feeds power. The better you are the more opportunity you have to improve yourself. ie you can kill mobs easier, people group with you more vs other wizards in your guild. Guild members make more of an effort to help you get keys (eg non solo VT parts) and flags (botting etc). Adding spell damage to the normal servers makes the game even more competitive.<br>
<br>
I do know people who have found this to stressful and drop out of guilds and or stop playing altogether. Is this what EQ is all about? What about the fun/social factor?<br>
<br>
 <p>Moozoo Sorcerer<br>
